      {
        "id": "3d1fc379237f7ac190f20a455a95934cf2781916",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-07 20:36:03.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nMeant to add: I read somewhere recently that a \"salt\" should always be added when encrypting a password.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "a0cfe4182bcc2fe0a5e45db425612e67df9cf6ad",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1761,
          "name": "Joseph Chou",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jc2555@att.com",
          "username": "jc2555"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-07 20:50:52.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nabout encrypt password with salt, is salt similar to secretKey in our code? Here is an article about encrypt password with salt: https://examples.javacodegeeks.com/core-java/security/encrypt-decrypt-with-salt/",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "fba34f08bce46411e6c70cfd61dfb928a944f459",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-07 21:10:23.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> about encrypt password with salt, is salt similar to secretKey in\n > our code? Here is an article about encrypt password with salt:\n > https://examples.javacodegeeks.com/core-java/security/encrypt-decrypt-with-salt/\n\nNo, salt is not the same as the secret key.  The salt causes a new encrypted string to be generated every time \"encrypt\" is called, thus making it more difficult for someone to guess the key.  This article is better:\nhttps://www.digizol.com/2009/10/java-encrypt-decrypt-jce-salt.html\n\nHowever, a simple way to do it is to generate a fixed-length salt and preppend or append it to the text to be encrypted.  After decrypting, just strip off the salt.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "990344985e56fa2c2ad144b384b40a3df4760d9e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1761,
          "name": "Joseph Chou",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jc2555@att.com",
          "username": "jc2555"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-07 21:25:20.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI believe adding salt would make it more secure, this implementation is secure enough the main purpose is to encrypt/decrypt password not use it to encrypt highly classified national security data. ECOMP Clamp team has similar implementation without salt so this implementation is secure enough.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
